<li><a href="#orgabdcb5d">57. Possible questions that can be asked about crossing network trades and their answers:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgd0ebcfc">57.1. Question: What is a crossing network trade?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orge4080ef">57.1.1. Answer:A crossing network trade is a type of trade that occurs between two parties without being routed through an exchange or other public displayed market. This means that the trade is not visible to other market participants, and it can be executed at a price that is different from the current market price.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgf288e4d">57.2. Question: What are the advantages of crossing network trades?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org0c67f7e">57.2.1. Answer: There are a number of advantages to crossing network trades, including:</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgc3511a5">57.3. Question: What are the disadvantages of crossing network trades?</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org6fda9ae">57.3.1. Answer: There are also a number of disadvantages to crossing network trades, including:</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org7627e96">57.4. Question: What are some examples of crossing network trades?</a></li>
<li><a href="#org0187280">57.5. Question: can you kindly explain me about logged and crossed trades</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org2bea1a6">57.5.1. Answer: A logged trade</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgd0a3852">58. Locked and/or crossed trades, regulation, penalty, and exceptions.</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org9599f0d">58.1. Regulation</a></li>
<li><a href="#orgbdbf9cb">58.2. Penalty</a></li>
<li><a href="#org59e2437">58.3. Exceptions</a></li>
<li><a href="#orgf7f6515">58.4. Question: can you give me a detailed example it should be in sequence of trading step by step with some real world number for scenario 1 when two parties agree to trade a security at a specific price scenario two when a market maker is forced to buy or sell a security at the price as another Market maker this is in context of locked and or crossed trades</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#org701090b">59. Detailed examples of locked and/or crossed trades:</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#org08a7419">59.1. Question: in the cross street example a customer came to Market maker to buy shares not to sell so how can mm or Market maker is forced to buy the shares from the customer</a>
<ul>
<li><a href="#orgbe97a60">59.1.1. Answer:You're right, the customer in the cross trade example is coming to the market maker to buy shares, not to sell them. However, the market maker is still forced to buy the shares from the customer because they are the only market maker who is quoting a price for the shares.</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orgf1106f2">59.2. Question: How can customers sell the shares when he don't have he came to Market maker to buy and at the end Market maker is trying to buy from the same customer who's trying to come to buy from him it's it's confusing</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a href="#orge983a09">60. Cross trade example :</a></li>
